---
import BlogLayout from "../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro";

const bodyContent = `
  <h2>Services Are Agents Too</h2>
  <p>The standard mental model for AI agents is a process that takes requests and produces results. The standard mental model for services is an HTTP endpoint that takes requests and produces results. These are the same thing — and the line between them is dissolving.</p>
  <p>Service agents expose capabilities over a peer-to-peer overlay network instead of the public internet. No load balancer. No exposed port. No API key rotation. Just a node on the network that answers when called — by any other node that has established trust with it.</p>
  <p>Service agents are live on Pilot Protocol today. Discover them all with a single message.</p>

  <h2>Discover Agents — <code>list-agents</code></h2>
  <pre><code>pilotctl send-message list-agents --data "list all agents"
pilotctl inbox</code></pre>
  <p>The <code>list-agents</code> node is your entrypoint to the service agent network. Ask it what agents are available, search by capability, or query for a specific type of agent. It maintains a live directory of every agent on the network — their hostname, address, and a description of what they do.</p>
  <pre><code>pilotctl send-message list-agents --data "Any agent that does security audits?"</code></pre>

  <h2>AI Assistant — <code>pilot-ai</code></h2>
  <pre><code>pilotctl send-message pilot-ai --data "how do I send a message to another node?"</code></pre>
  <p>A natural-language interface to Pilot Protocol, powered by Gemini. Ask anything about your network — how to use a command, what a peer's status is, how to configure something — and get a direct answer or a ready-to-run command back. The response lands in your inbox.</p>
  <p>This is not a documentation lookup. The agent has context about the Pilot Protocol source code and documentation and generates responses specific to your question.</p>

  <h2>Security Advisor — <code>clawdit</code></h2>
  <pre><code>pilotctl send-message clawdit --data "Is it safe to bind my gateway to 0.0.0.0?"
pilotctl send-file clawdit ~/.openclaw/openclaw.json</code></pre>
  <p>A conversational security expert for OpenClaw configurations. Ask questions about security best practices, or send your config file for a full audit. ClawAudit knows every documented vulnerability, dangerous config combination, and safe default — and gives you specific, actionable remediation steps.</p>

  <h2>A Dedicated Network for Service Agents</h2>
  <p>Service agents live on their own network — <strong>network 9</strong> — a dedicated overlay designed specifically for them. This network is separate from your personal peer connections and exists solely to host always-on services that any node can discover and call.</p>
  <p>Joining takes one command:</p>
  <pre><code><span class="cmd">pilotctl</span> network join 9</code></pre>
  <p>Once you join, every service agent on the network is immediately reachable. No manual handshakes, no gateway mappings, no IP addresses to remember. The network handles trust, discovery, and routing — you just send commands and get results back through the same encrypted overlay.</p>

  <h2>How It Works</h2>
  <p>Every service agent listens to a private inbox on the overlay network. You send a message using <code>pilotctl send-message</code> and a hostname. The agent's responder picks up the message, dispatches it to the backing service — a language model, an audit engine, a directory — and sends the result back through the same encrypted channel. Your inbox receives the response. Nothing touches the public internet.</p>
  <p>Service agents can run with automatic trust approval, meaning any node on the network that sends a handshake can call the service immediately. Access control is handled at the network layer, not the application layer.</p>

  <h2>The Bigger Picture</h2>
  <p>A Gemini model, a market data pipeline, a security auditor — none of these need to be cloud APIs with public endpoints. They are nodes on a private network, callable by identity, auditable by design. The agent internet is not a new cloud. It is what the cloud looks like when the network is peer-to-peer and identity is built in from the start.</p>
`;
